.TH MOUNT 1 "2026-05-18" "SlateOS" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
mount \- mount a filesystem
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B mount
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fIDEVICE\fR \fIMOUNTPOINT\fR
.br
.B mount
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fB\-a\fR
.SH DESCRIPTION
Attach the filesystem found on DEVICE at the directory MOUNTPOINT.
Only the superuser or users with the appropriate capability may mount
filesystems.
.PP
Without arguments, \fBmount\fR lists all currently mounted filesystems.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\fB\-t\fR \fITYPE\fR
Specify the filesystem type (e.g. ext4, fat32, tmpfs).
.TP
\fB\-o\fR \fIOPTIONS\fR
Mount options, comma-separated (e.g. ro, noexec, nosuid).
.TP
\fB\-a\fR
Mount all filesystems listed in /etc/fstab.
.TP
\fB\-r\fR, \fB\-\-read\-only\fR
Mount the filesystem read-only.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Verbose mode.
.TP
\fB\-\-bind\fR
Bind mount: make a directory available at another location.
.SH EXAMPLES
.nf
mount                         List mounted filesystems
mount /dev/sda1 /mnt          Mount a partition
mount -t ext4 /dev/sdb1 /data Mount ext4 filesystem
mount -o ro /dev/sr0 /cdrom   Mount read-only
mount -a                      Mount all from /etc/fstab
.fi
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR umount (8),
.BR fstab (5),
.BR df (1)
.SH AUTHOR
SlateOS Contributors.
